    "summary": "Nubian Iron Smelting (c. 400–200 BC) at the [[event:1157|Kingdom of Meroe]] developed one of the ancient world's major iron-production industries, potentially making Meroe a key node in the diffusion of iron technology into sub-Saharan Africa and creating the material basis for the kingdom's military and economic power.\n\nThe evidence for Meroe's iron industry comes from the massive slag heaps found at the city — so extensive that early archaeologists called Meroe the 'Birmingham of Africa,' though this was an exaggeration. The smelting furnaces at Meroe used a sophisticated design capable of producing high-quality iron. Whether Meroitic iron technology spread southward into sub-Saharan Africa — or whether sub-Saharan Africans developed iron smelting independently (as now seems likely in several regions, potentially before Meroe) — remains debated in archaeology. What is clear is that Meroe's iron production was substantial and that the kingdom's access to iron gave it military advantages over neighbors who lacked the technology. The industry contributed to Meroe's wealth and its ability to maintain independence from Ptolemaic Egypt and later Roman Egypt, including defeating a Roman punitive expedition in 24 BC.",
